<body>
  <sec sec-type="introduction" id="s1">
    <title>INTRODUCTION</title>
    <p>Regulation of gene expression at the RNA level is achieved by regulating rates of RNA synthesis and degradation (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC27" ref-type="bibr">Garneau et al. 2007</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC76" ref-type="bibr">Weake and Workman 2010</xref>). An increase in the abundance of an RNA transcript could result from an increase in the transcript's synthesis rate or a decrease in its degradation rate (i.e., transcript stabilization). Therefore, understanding the mechanisms that underly gene expression regulation requires methods to identify changes in RNA levels as well as changes in the kinetics of RNA metabolism.</p>
    <p>While standard RNA-seq can identify changes in RNA levels, specialized sequencing-based techniques are required to rigorously investigate the kinetic causes of those changes (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC26" ref-type="bibr">Furlan et al. 2021</xref>). Metabolic labeling with nucleotide analogs followed by enrichment and sequencing of labeled RNA is one such strategy (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC17" ref-type="bibr">Dolken et al. 2008</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC59" ref-type="bibr">Rabani et al. 2011</xref>, <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC60" ref-type="bibr">2014</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC77" ref-type="bibr">Windhager et al. 2012</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC16" ref-type="bibr">de Pretis et al. 2015</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC18" ref-type="bibr">Duffy et al. 2015</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC44" ref-type="bibr">Lugowski et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC33" ref-type="bibr">Hersch et al. 2022</xref>). Further innovation was needed because these enrichment-based techniques require substantial amounts of starting RNA, introduce biochemical biases during enrichment, and cannot distinguish the desired enriched RNAs from nontrivial levels of contamination (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC75" ref-type="bibr">Wada and Becskei 2017</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC19" ref-type="bibr">Duffy et al. 2019</xref>). Previously, our laboratory and others addressed this shortcoming by developing nucleotide recoding RNA-seq methods (NR-seq) (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF1" ref-type="fig">Fig. 1</xref>A). These techniques combine s<sup>4</sup>U metabolic labeling and nucleotide recoding chemistry (TimeLapse [<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC66" ref-type="bibr">Schofield et al. 2018</xref>], SLAM [<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC34" ref-type="bibr">Herzog et al. 2017</xref>], TUC [<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC63" ref-type="bibr">Riml et al. 2017</xref>], etc.) to either convert or disrupt the hydrogen bonding pattern of incorporated s<sup>4</sup>U. This yields apparent T-to-C mutations in the RNA-seq data that indicate sites of s<sup>4</sup>U incorporation and can be used to estimate the fraction of extracted RNA that was synthesized after the introduction of metabolic label (hereafter, fraction new) (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC36" ref-type="bibr">Jurges et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC66" ref-type="bibr">Schofield et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC55" ref-type="bibr">Neumann et al. 2019</xref>). This adds kinetic information to the snapshot provided by RNA-seq while eliminating the need for enrichment of labeled RNA.</p>
    <fig position="float" id="RNA079451VOCF1">
      <label>FIGURE 1.</label>
      <caption>
        <p>NR-seq can be used to identify differential RNA kinetics. (<italic>A</italic>) Schematic of a typical NR-seq experiment. At steady-state, the fraction new has a simple relationship with the degradation rate constant. (<italic>B</italic>) Statistical modeling provides estimates of RNA kinetic parameters. In this anecdotal example, Transcript A is less stable in the Experimental condition than in the Reference condition. Combining differential stability analysis with differential expression analysis yields differential RNA synthesis analysis.</p>
      </caption>
      <graphic xlink:href="958f01" position="float"/>
    </fig>
    <p>NR-seq provides an approach to perform differential kinetic analyses that complement differential expression analyses (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF1" ref-type="fig">Fig. 1</xref>B). Rigorous differential kinetic analysis requires a statistical tool that compares replicates of NR-seq data collected in two or more different biological conditions. Such a tool would have to be robust to the low number of replicates commonly used in high-throughput experiments as well as the unique challenges of NR-seq (variability in mutation rates, sequencing errors, heteroskedastic replicate variability, etc.). While there is currently no such tool, several studies provide useful frameworks for interpreting NR-seq data (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC74" ref-type="bibr">Uvarovskii and Dieterich 2017</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC36" ref-type="bibr">Jurges et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC66" ref-type="bibr">Schofield et al. 2018</xref>). Furthermore, we reasoned that developing such a tool can be guided by numerous advances in the analysis of RNA-seq data to identify differences in RNA levels (i.e., differential expression analysis) (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC6" ref-type="bibr">Berge et al. 2019</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC69" ref-type="bibr">Stark et al. 2019</xref>). In particular, statistical analyses of differential expression are designed to address two important challenges. First, signal is distinguished from background using a statistical model that provides accurate estimates of replicate variability in RNA-seq read counts (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC15" ref-type="bibr">Costa-Silva et al. 2017</xref>). Second, analyses can compensate for the low number of replicates typically collected for RNA-seq by using transcriptome-wide trends to improve transcript-specific parameter estimates (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC14" ref-type="bibr">Conesa et al. 2016</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC37" ref-type="bibr">Katahira 2016</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC40" ref-type="bibr">Li and Li 2018</xref>). Software implementing such analyses (DESeq2 [<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC43" ref-type="bibr">Love et al. 2014</xref>], edgeR [<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC65" ref-type="bibr">Robinson et al. 2010</xref>], limma [<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC64" ref-type="bibr">Ritchie et al. 2015</xref>], etc.) have become an integral part of almost any RNA-seq experiment, bringing statistical rigor and reproducibility to these high-throughput investigations. New analogous tools are needed for NR-seq data to achieve similar rigor.</p>
    <p>To address this need, we developed bakR (Bayesian analysis of the kinetics of RNA), an R package that implements an improved statistical model together with multiple-test adjusted null hypothesis testing to perform differential kinetic analysis. bakR consists of three different implementations of a novel Bayesian hierarchical model that we developed to share information across transcripts in high-throughput NR-seq data sets. These implementations allow for both rapid preliminary investigations and more highly powered analyses of differential RNA kinetics. We used a panel of simulated reference and experimental data sets to validate all implementations. We also compared these implementations with implementations we developed that use existing models to perform kinetic parameter estimation prior to differential kinetic analysis (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC74" ref-type="bibr">Uvarovskii and Dieterich 2017</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC36" ref-type="bibr">Jurges et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC66" ref-type="bibr">Schofield et al. 2018</xref>). We found that the bakR implementations consistently outperformed similarly efficient implementations of existing models. Finally, we analyzed existing NR-seq data sets with bakR and found that it significantly improved and facilitated the identification of differential stability signal, independent of the NR-seq method used. bakR represents an important new tool for assessing changes in the kinetics of RNA synthesis and degradation.</p>
  </sec>
  <sec sec-type="results" id="s2">
    <title>RESULTS</title>
    <sec id="s2a">
      <title>Adapting existing models and developing a new hierarchical model of NR-seq data</title>
      <p>We developed bakR to identify differences in transcript metabolic kinetics by analyzing data from a simple and widely used design for NR-seq experiments (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC34" ref-type="bibr">Herzog et al. 2017</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC52" ref-type="bibr">Muhar et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC66" ref-type="bibr">Schofield et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC46" ref-type="bibr">Luo et al. 2020</xref>, <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC47" ref-type="bibr">2021</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC53" ref-type="bibr">Na et al. 2020</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC56" ref-type="bibr">Olivero et al. 2020</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC73" ref-type="bibr">Thiecke et al. 2020</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC81" ref-type="bibr">Zimmer et al. 2021</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC9" ref-type="bibr">Biancon et al. 2022</xref>) in which cells are treated with a metabolic label for an amount of time referred to as the label time (<italic>t</italic><sub>label</sub>) (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF1" ref-type="fig">Fig. 1</xref>A). bakR quantifies how RNA kinetics impacts NR-seq data with a previously used steady-state model of RNA dynamics (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC34" ref-type="bibr">Herzog et al. 2017</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC36" ref-type="bibr">Jurges et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC66" ref-type="bibr">Schofield et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC19" ref-type="bibr">Duffy et al. 2019</xref>). In this model, the amount of RNA synthesized during metabolic labeling (RNA<sub>new</sub>) observes first order single rate constant degradation and zeroth order constant rate synthesis kinetics, captured in this differential equation:
<disp-formula id="RNA079451VOCUM1"><mml:math id="UM1" display="block" overflow="scroll"><mml:mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0"><mml:mrow><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">dRN</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">new</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">dt</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:mrow><mml:mspace width="0.4em"/><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mspace width="0.4em"/><mml:msub><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">syn</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mspace width="0.4em"/><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:mspace width="0.4em"/><mml:msub><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">deg</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mspace width="0.4em"/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mspace width="0.4em"/><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">RN</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">new</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo></mml:mstyle></mml:math></disp-formula>
which has the following solution, assuming an initial RNA<sub>new</sub> concentration of zero:
<disp-formula id="RNA079451VOCUM2"><mml:math id="UM2" display="block" overflow="scroll"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">RN</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">A</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">new</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mspace width="0.4em"/><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mspace width="0.4em"/><mml:mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0"><mml:mrow><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">syn</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">deg</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mspace width="0.4em"/><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:mspace width="0.4em"/><mml:msup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">deg</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:msup></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mstyle></mml:math></disp-formula>
</p>
      <p>If RNA levels are assumed to be at steady-state, meaning that the total RNA concentration during the experiment is the ratio of <italic>k</italic><sub>syn</sub> to <italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>, the fraction new (denoted <italic>θ</italic>) is
<disp-formula id="RNA079451VOCUM3"><mml:math id="UM3" display="block" overflow="scroll"><mml:mi>θ</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>−</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>k</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">deg</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">label</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:math></disp-formula>
</p>
      <p>Therefore, to estimate <italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub> (in absolute units of inverse time, since <italic>θ</italic> is dimensionless), <italic>θ</italic> must be estimated. <italic>k</italic><sub>syn</sub> (in relative units of normalized read count per unit time) can then be estimated using the <italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub> estimate and the total RNA concentration (estimated using read counts).</p>
      <p>Estimating <italic>θ</italic> relies on the property that sequencing reads from new transcripts will have on average more T-to-C mutations than reads from old transcripts. We considered implementing one of the existing models of NR-seq mutational data to estimate <italic>θ</italic> prior to differential kinetic analysis: pulseR's complete pooling negative binomial (CPNB) model and a slight modification of <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC66" ref-type="bibr">Schofield et al. (2018)</xref> and GRAND-SLAM's nonhierarchical mixture model (NHPMM) (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF2" ref-type="fig">Fig. 2</xref>A; for naming rationale and implementation details, see <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Methods</ext-link>). In addition, we were inspired by models of differential expression to develop implementations of a new hierarchical mixture model (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF2" ref-type="fig">Fig. 2</xref>A,B).</p>
      <fig position="float" id="RNA079451VOCF2">
        <label>FIGURE 2.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>Considering five implementations of new and existing statistical models for bakR. (<italic>A</italic>) Names given to the five models/implementations considered for bakR. Columns of hypothetical data are gene/transcript name (RNA ID), sample name (S), number of Ts in cDNA read (<italic>n</italic>T), number of T-to-C mutations (TC), number of reads with identical data (<italic>n</italic>). BH stands for Benjamini–Hochberg multiple test adjustment. *<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC66" ref-type="bibr">Schofield et al. (2018)</xref>/GRAND-SLAM model is a U-content adjusted Poisson mixture model rather than the original binomial mixture model. See Materials and Methods and <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Methods</ext-link> for details. (<italic>B</italic>) Pictorial description of the new hierarchical mixture model we developed. Mutations in sequencing reads are modeled as coming from a two-component U-content adjusted Poisson distribution mixture model. Partial pooling across fraction new and variance estimates in a given replicate is performed to make use of the high-throughput nature of NR-seq data sets.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="958f02" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>Our new hierarchical model was designed to address key limitations of the existing models. The CPNB model assumes that sequencing reads can be unambiguously identified as s<sup>4</sup>U labeled or unlabeled. While this approximation is reasonably accurate in cases of high label incorporation and relatively long reads, it is problematic when faced with lower label incorporation rates and/or shorter (e.g., &lt;50-nt) reads (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC62" ref-type="bibr">Reichholf et al. 2019</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC81" ref-type="bibr">Zimmer et al. 2021</xref>). Our laboratory originally addressed this shortcoming by developing a two-component mixture model that accounts for overlap in the mutational distributions of old and new sequencing reads (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC66" ref-type="bibr">Schofield et al. 2018</xref>) and that <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC36" ref-type="bibr">Jurges et al. (2018)</xref> implemented in the single sample analysis software GRAND-SLAM. Despite this improvement, the original mixture model only directly quantifies uncertainty in the fraction new (<italic>θ</italic>) estimate in each replicate and does not attempt to model replicate variability [RV; defined as the standard deviation of the logit(<italic>θ</italic>) estimates] (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF3" ref-type="fig">Fig. 3</xref>A), an important source of uncertainty in high-throughput, low-replicate number experiments. Thus, we considered strategies to improve uncertainty quantification and directly model mutational data while developing bakR.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="RNA079451VOCF3">
        <label>FIGURE 3.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>Using a replicate variability trend in NR-seq data to improve uncertainty quantification. (<italic>A</italic>) Replicate variability (RV) is defined as the standard deviation of logit(<italic>θ</italic>) estimates across replicates. (<italic>B</italic>) RV estimates (using typical sample standard deviation estimator) for individual transcripts in an NR-seq data set compared with sequencing read counts. (<italic>C</italic>) Estimates of average RV for groups of transcripts with similar sequencing depths. (<italic>D</italic>) Effect of partial pooling on RV estimate variability. For three transcripts (slightly larger points circled in black), the extent of RV regularization is depicted with an arrow from the naïve estimate to the hierarchical model's estimate.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="958f03" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>NR-seq experiments are typically done with only a few replicates, making it difficult to estimate replicate variabilities for individual transcripts (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC42" ref-type="bibr">Lonnstedt and Speed 2002</xref>). Differential expression analyses for standard RNA-seq have addressed this challenge by sharing replicate variability information across transcripts (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC65" ref-type="bibr">Robinson et al. 2010</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC43" ref-type="bibr">Love et al. 2014</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC64" ref-type="bibr">Ritchie et al. 2015</xref>). We were particularly inspired by the use of a trend in the replicate variability as a function of sequencing depth that is implemented in limma (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC64" ref-type="bibr">Ritchie et al. 2015</xref>), DSS (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC78" ref-type="bibr">Wu et al. 2013</xref>), and DESeq2 (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC43" ref-type="bibr">Love et al. 2014</xref>); therefore, we examined whether there is a similar trend in NR-seq data sets. We found a striking power law relationship between the logit(<italic>θ</italic>) replicate variability (RV) and the number of sequencing reads mapping to a transcript (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF3" ref-type="fig">Fig. 3</xref>B,C; <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S1</ext-link>). In our Bayesian hierarchical model, this trend is used as an informative prior learned from the data that improves RV estimates (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF3" ref-type="fig">Fig. 3</xref>D), providing a more accurate separation of signal from background.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="s2b">
      <title>Developing implementations prioritizing either efficiency or accuracy</title>
      <p>When considering computational implementations for bakR, we recognized that different applications are likely to favor different needs when balancing statistical rigor with computational efficiency. Therefore, we developed three implementations of the novel hierarchical model described above (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF2" ref-type="fig">Figs. 2</xref>, <xref rid="RNA079451VOCF4" ref-type="fig">4</xref>A). Efficient maximum likelihood estimation (MLE) combined with approximate partial pooling via analytical solutions to simple Bayesian models can provide quick but conservative initial investigations of NR-seq data sets. A more sensitive but less efficient full Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) implementation using the probabilistic programming language Stan (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC30" ref-type="bibr">Gelman et al. 2015</xref>) can provide a more comprehensive statistical analysis. Finally, we reasoned that a hybrid approach (Hybrid implementation) that combines features of the MLE and MCMC implementations might perform similarly to the MCMC implementation on most data sets while being significantly more efficient. See Materials and Methods and <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Methods</ext-link> for further details regarding all implementations. The CPNB implementation is of similar efficiency to that of the MLE implementation and the NHPMM implementation is of similar efficiency to that of the MCMC implementation (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Table S1</ext-link>). We next examined the performance of these potential bakR implementations.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="RNA079451VOCF4">
        <label>FIGURE 4.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>Development and validation of three distinct computational implementations of the Bayesian hierarchical model. (<italic>A</italic>) Fundamental tradeoff exists between efficiency and rigor of a statistical model's computational implementation. bakR uses three distinct computational implementations that cover the efficiency versus rigor spectrum. (<italic>B</italic>) Accuracy of <italic>θ</italic> estimates for the three implementations of the new hierarchical model. Diagonal line is <italic>y</italic> = <italic>x</italic>. (<italic>C</italic>) L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) calibration for all three implementations of the new hierarchical model. The <italic>x</italic>-axis represents the marginal posterior probability mass covered by the L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) credible interval and the <italic>y</italic>-axis is the percentage of transcripts whose true L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) fall within the credible interval. Five hundred lines obtained from bootstrapped samples of 1000 transcripts from a total of 10,000 transcripts are depicted for each implementation.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="958f04" position="float"/>
      </fig>
    </sec>
    <sec id="s2c">
      <title>Validation of all five implementations using simulated data</title>
      <p>We used simulated data to assess the accuracy of all implementations considered for bakR (see Materials and Methods for simulation details). Briefly, we used a generative model that captures trends seen in real NR-seq data sets. We simulated two replicates of NR-seq data for 10,000 transcripts and two experimental conditions (e.g., control and treated samples). We analyzed the simulated data with all five implementations. This analysis revealed strong correlations between the estimates and the true simulated values (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF4" ref-type="fig">Fig. 4</xref>B; <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S2</ext-link>), confirming that <italic>θ</italic> estimates from the three implementations of the new hierarchical model were accurate. <italic>θ</italic> estimate accuracy was found to be greater for simulated transcripts with more reads, as expected. The CPNB and NHPMM estimates were also generally accurate, though the CPNB estimates were worse for transcripts with <italic>θ</italic> further from 0.5 (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S3</ext-link>). This is likely due to pulseR's assumption that labeled and unlabeled reads can be definitively identified. In summary, <italic>θ</italic> was well estimated by all implementations, especially those directly modeling the mutational data.</p>
      <p>As bakR is the first NR-seq analysis tool to perform differential kinetic analysis, we next confirmed that estimates of log<sub>2</sub>-fold changes in the degradation rate constant [L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>)] were accurate and that uncertainties were properly quantified by all potential bakR implementations. To do this, we assessed the extent to which the credible/confidence intervals provided by the five implementations contained the true L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) with the expected probability (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF4" ref-type="fig">Fig. 4</xref>C; <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S3</ext-link>). For example, the 50% credible interval should contain the simulated L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) 50% of the time, and we found this to be generally true for all implementations. This further suggests that all models are properly implemented.</p>
      <p>Finally, a benefit of Stan's implementation of auxiliary variable MCMC, used by the NHPMM, Hybrid, and MCMC implementations, is that it provides extensive model diagnostics (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC10" ref-type="bibr">Brooks et al. 2011</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC29" ref-type="bibr">Gelman 2014</xref>). These diagnostics can be used to confirm that all model parameters are accurately estimated with the data provided. When analyzing simulated data, these sampling diagnostics indicated that this was the case (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S4, S5</ext-link>). Together, these results support the conclusion that the models are all well implemented.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="s2d">
      <title>Simulated data comparison of models and implementations</title>
      <p>We next determined which of the five models/implementations to include in bakR by comparing their ability to distinguish differential stability signal from null background in multiple simulated data sets. We simulated data for 10,000 transcripts, of which 10% were simulated to have differential degradation kinetics [differences in stability between a reference and experimental condition; simulated L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) magnitudes typically ranged from just above 0 to just under 3], two biological replicates of data, and three different read count versus replicate variability trends (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF5" ref-type="fig">Fig. 5</xref>, top row; see Materials and Methods for simulation details). These replicate variability trends represent the range of trends we have seen in real NR-seq data sets. The false discovery rate (FDR, percentage of transcripts identified by the models as hits that were false positives) and power (percentage of transcripts with differential kinetics identified as hits by the models) of all models were assessed at a range of significance cutoffs (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF5" ref-type="fig">Fig. 5</xref>, second and third rows, respectively). FDR was calculated at a wider range of cutoffs to assess the extent to which FDR was controlled, as the ideal case is a <italic>y</italic> = <italic>x</italic> relationship between <italic>P</italic><sub>adj</sub> cutoff and FDR. Power was calculated for a range of commonly used significance cutoffs (<italic>P</italic><sub>adj</sub> &lt; 0.01 to <italic>P</italic><sub>adj</sub> &lt; 0.1). We also compared Matthew's correlation coefficients (MCC) (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC49" ref-type="bibr">Matthews 1975</xref>) of all the models at a common significance cutoff of 0.05 (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF5" ref-type="fig">Fig. 5</xref>, bottom row). The MCC is more informative than other popular binary classification metrics (e.g., F<sub>1</sub> score and model accuracy) as it accounts for the relative abundances of all four categories of classifications (i.e., false positives, false negatives, true positives, and true negatives) (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC13" ref-type="bibr">Chicco and Jurman 2020</xref>).</p>
      <fig position="float" id="RNA079451VOCF5">
        <label>FIGURE 5.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>bakR implementations outperform extensions of existing models. (<italic>Top</italic>) Simulated RV versus read count trend. ln(RV) for each transcript is drawn from a normal distribution centered on the trend with standard deviation of 0.05. Gray bar around trend represents typical range of simulated replicate variabilities. (Second row) False discovery rate (FDR) as a function of significance cutoff for all implementations. (Third row) Power as a function of significance cutoff for all implementations. The average FDR and Power for five simulation replicates are plotted at each cutoff. (<italic>Bottom</italic>) Matthew's Correlation Coefficient (MCC) at a <italic>P</italic><sub>adj</sub> cutoff of 0.05 for all implementations tested. Colored points represent MCC for the analysis of one replicate. Black point is average MCC and bars represent one standard error above and below the mean.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="958f05" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>In all cases, we found that FDRs were well controlled by the Hybrid and MCMC implementations (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF5" ref-type="fig">Fig. 5</xref>). FDRs for the NHPMM implementation were slightly inflated. Despite this, the NHPMM implementation was still significantly underpowered relative to the Hybrid and MCMC implementations. In other words, the Hybrid and MCMC implementations identified more signal and filtered out more null transcripts than the NHPMM implementation. Therefore, we decided that the Hybrid and MCMC implementations were optimal for analyses of NR-seq data sets.</p>
      <p>Comparing the more efficient implementations (MLE and CPNB), FDRs were generally well controlled in both cases, though became more inflated for the CPNB implementation when analyzing simulated data with steeper read count versus replicate variability trends (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF5" ref-type="fig">Fig. 5</xref>). The statistical power and MCCs of these implementations were also comparable. Increasing the amount of variability in the replicate variability, decreasing s<sup>4</sup>U incorporation rates, and increasing the number of replicates did not significantly alter the relative performance of these implementations (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF5" ref-type="fig">Fig. 5</xref>; <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S6</ext-link>). Due to its improved kinetic parameter estimation accuracy (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF4" ref-type="fig">Fig. 4</xref>B; <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S3</ext-link>), robustness to different heteroskedastic trends (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF5" ref-type="fig">Fig. 5</xref>), superior efficiency (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Table S1</ext-link>), and compatibility with the Hybrid implementation, we included the MLE implementation and not the CPNB implementation in bakR. Thus, bakR includes the MLE, Hybrid, and MCMC implementations.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="s2e">
      <title>bakR MCMC implementation is more robust to low mutation rates than other implementations</title>
      <p>When experimental design is suboptimal, the utility of data from NR-seq experiments can be limited by low s<sup>4</sup>U incorporation and conversion rates. To assess the impact of this type of experimental shortcoming on the ability of bakR to identify differential kinetics, we simulated three data sets with three different <italic>p</italic><sub>news</sub> (the probability that a U in a new read is mutated to a C) of 1%, 0.7%, and 0.4%. We analyzed these data sets with all five implementations and assessed fraction new estimation accuracy and ability to identify differential stability.</p>
      <p>We found that the fraction new estimation accuracies of all implementations were negatively impacted by decreasing <italic>p</italic><sub>new</sub> (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S7–S9</ext-link>). Despite this, the fraction new estimates of three of the mixture model implementations (MLE, MCMC, and NHPMM) were consistently unbiased. The Hybrid implementation's fraction new estimates were less biased for higher coverage features (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S7–S9</ext-link>). For lower coverage features, the Hybrid implementation's estimates were biased toward the population average, with lower <italic>p</italic><sub>news</sub> leading to a larger bias. This is likely due to the MLE implementation significantly overestimating fraction new uncertainties at lower coverage, leading to excessive regularization by the Hybrid implementation's hierarchical model (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S10</ext-link>). The CPNB implementation consistently underestimated fraction news, with the magnitude of underestimation being larger at lower <italic>p</italic><sub>new</sub>. This can be ascribed to pulseR's assumption that labeled and unlabeled reads can be definitively identified. In summary, while low <italic>p</italic><sub>news</sub> decrease the accuracy of any analysis of NR-seq, bakR implementations can still provide accurate estimates of the fraction new for high coverage (&gt;5000 reads per sample) features with low <italic>p</italic><sub>new</sub> values (0.4%).</p>
      <p>As with fraction new estimation, lower <italic>p</italic><sub>new</sub> values hampered identification of differential kinetics. All implementations became increasingly conservative (lower power and FDR) with decreasing <italic>p</italic><sub>new</sub>. At a very low <italic>p</italic><sub>new</sub> of 0.7% the MLE, CPNB, and NHPMM implementations were all unable to detect almost any instances of differential stability (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S11–S13</ext-link>). The MCMC and Hybrid implementations on the other hand retained nonzero statistical power at lower <italic>p</italic><sub>news</sub> (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S11–S13</ext-link>). Only the MCMC implementation was still able to properly identify some instances of differential stability at the lowest <italic>p</italic><sub>new</sub> tested (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S11, S12</ext-link>). To assist users analyzing data from experiments with suboptimal incorporation rates, bakR will suggest using the MCMC implementation when <italic>p</italic><sub>news</sub> are low in one or more samples to maximize the sensitivity of their analyses. bakR will also warn users of the unavoidable difficulty of interpreting NR-seq data with low <italic>p</italic><sub>new</sub>, as these challenges may be best overcome with improved upstream experimental design.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="s2f">
      <title>Testing and improving the robustness of bakR to deviations from model assumptions</title>
      <p>Two potential sources of variance that could affect the performance of bakR are U-to-U differences in s<sup>4</sup>U incorporation propensity and read-to-read differences in T-content. In regards to the former, bakR as well as all existing strategies for analyzing NR-seq assume that every uridine in cellular RNA is equally likely to be replaced by s<sup>4</sup>U and converted to a species that behaves like a cytosine during reverse transcription. It is possible that various factors (local sequence context, secondary structure, etc.) could lead to deviations from this assumption. We analyzed U-specific mutation rates in published TimeLapse-seq data from WT HEK293T cells to assess the extent of such deviations in real data (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC46" ref-type="bibr">Luo et al. 2020</xref>). We found that U-specific mutation rates were slightly more variable than expected by a model in which every U in a given transcript is equally mutable (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S14</ext-link>). Because of this, we simulated data sets with moderate and high amounts of U-to-U mutation rate variability and assessed the robustness of all three bakR implementations to these deviations (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S15–S17</ext-link>; see <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Methods</ext-link> for simulation details). We found that fraction new estimation accuracy and differential stability identification was largely unaffected by even large amounts of U-to-U mutation rate variability (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S14–S17</ext-link>). bakR is thus robust to deviations from the assumption of sample-wide old and new read mutation rates.</p>
      <p>In regards to read-to-read T-content variability, bakR models mutational data with a U-content (T-content in the sequenced cDNA) adjusted Poisson mixture model. In the MCMC implementation, a U-content adjustment factor is calculated for each transcript, while the MLE and Hybrid implementations calculate this factor for each group of reads mapped to the same transcript and containing the same number of mutations (see Materials and Methods for details). In both cases, bakR is assuming minimal read-to-read T-content variability. All simulations include some read-to-read T-content variability (see Materials and Methods for details), suggesting that bakR is robust to moderate deviations from this assumption. We assessed how robust bakR was to larger amounts of read-to-read T-content variability by analyzing two simulated data sets with more extreme amounts of read-to-read T-content variability (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S18–S20</ext-link>; see <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Methods</ext-link> for simulation details). We found that the MCMC implementation was less robust to large amounts of read-specific T-content variability than the MLE and Hybrid implementations. We reasoned this was due to the differences in U-content adjustment factor calculation, and thus implemented the MLE's U-content adjustment strategy in the MCMC implementation. Reanalyzing the simulated data sets with this change reduced fraction new estimation bias and improved the MCMC's identification of differential stability (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S21–S23</ext-link>). Furthermore, this modification also reduced bias in the MLE and Hybrid implementations’ fraction new estimation accuracy, as these methods rely on mutation rate estimates derived from a nonhierarchical version of the MCMC mixture model (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S21, S22</ext-link>). We were thus able to increase the robustness of all bakR implementations to large amounts of read-to-read T-content variability.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="s2g">
      <title>bakR MCMC and Hybrid implementations outperform other implementations on real data</title>
      <p>We sought to assess the performance of bakR on real data sets. As ground truth assumptions are generally compromised by the complexities of biological phenomena, we constructed our own ground truth by comparing biological replicates of NR-seq data. We generated two such data sets: one consisting of four replicates of TimeLapse-seq data from wild-type HEL cells (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC9" ref-type="bibr">Biancon et al. 2022</xref>) in two batches (defined as slightly different experimental conditions) (see <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Methods</ext-link> and <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S24, S25</ext-link> for details), and one consisting of two independent sets (i.e., batches from separate studies) of TimeLapse-seq data collected from HEK293T cells (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC46" ref-type="bibr">Luo et al. 2020</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC53" ref-type="bibr">Na et al. 2020</xref>) in duplicate (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S24, S26</ext-link>). We assessed the correlation of fraction new estimates across all replicates and batches (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S25, S26</ext-link>). We found that while estimates correlated well in both data sets, the HEK293T data suffered from moderate batch effects, with one of the independent data sets yielding slightly higher average fraction new estimates than the other (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S26</ext-link>). We split the four replicates into two sets of two replicates, mixing batches to reduce the impact of batch effects, and generated real instances of differential stability by permuting the gene names of a subset of transcripts in the second set of replicates (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S24</ext-link>; see <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Methods</ext-link> for simulation details). These combined data sets provided us with the opportunity to quantitatively assess the performance of bakR on real NR-seq data.</p>
      <p>Analyzing the HEL replicates, we confirmed that the bakR MCMC and Hybrid implementations were better able to identify instances of differential stability than any other implementation tested (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S27</ext-link>, left half). The MLE implementation performed worse on this data set (lower power) than on many of the simulated data sets analyzed. This is likely due to the high level of unlabeled transcripts (average fraction new of 0.05) in this data. The uncertainty estimation strategy of the MLE implementation is more conservative for transcripts with extreme fraction news, that is, close to 0 or 1 (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S10</ext-link>). Despite this, the Hybrid implementation, which uses the MLE implementation's fraction new estimates and uncertainties, was still able to perform well. This further supports the conclusion that that the hierarchical modeling strategy implemented in bakR significantly increases the sensitivity of differential kinetic analyses.</p>
      <p>As with the HEL replicates, the analysis of HEK293T replicates with all implementations confirmed that the bakR MCMC and Hybrid implementations were best able to identify instances of differential stability (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S27</ext-link>, right half). To further test the robustness of all implementations, we generated three additional data sets with the HEK293T data in which the effect sizes were reduced by restricting the set of transcripts whose labels could be permuted, and in which the mutational data was downsampled to generate lower mutation rate data (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S26, S28</ext-link>). The MCMC and Hybrid implementations were consistently the two best performing implementations on these data sets as well (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S28</ext-link>). The CPNB implementation performed better in this case than on any previously analyzed data set, though this might be an artifact arising from the batch effects present in these data. Despite this, the CPNB implementation was much less robust to mutational downsampling than the MCMC and Hybrid implementations (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S28</ext-link>). Therefore, these analyses confirm that the bakR MCMC and Hybrid implementations outperform other approaches to assess differential stability in real data.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="s2h">
      <title>bakR improves and facilitates analyses of real NR-seq data sets</title>
      <p>We next examined whether the output of bakR on real data sets is consistent with known biology. We first reanalyzed TimeLapse-seq data with RNA collected from WT and <italic>DCP2</italic> knockout (KO) HEK293T cells (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC46" ref-type="bibr">Luo et al. 2020</xref>). The DCP2 enzyme catalyzes the removal of the 5′ protective cap of mRNA (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC20" ref-type="bibr">Dunckley and Parker 1999</xref>), so the expectation is that <italic>DCP2</italic> KO will lead to widespread stabilization of DCP2 mRNA substrates. Lacking a tool like bakR, <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC46" ref-type="bibr">Luo et al. (2020)</xref> developed an analysis strategy specialized for their data. This strategy was able to accurately quantify changes in degradation rate constants but lacked uncertainty quantification and thus relied on differential expression analysis and comparison of L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) versus L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>syn</sub>) magnitudes to identify stabilization (see Materials and Methods for details). Therefore, we hypothesized that bakR would provide a list of <italic>DCP2</italic> KO stabilized transcripts that was more consistent with the data.</p>
      <p>Reanalysis of the data from Luo et al. using all three bakR implementations confirmed that there was widespread stabilization of transcripts in the <italic>DCP2</italic> KO (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF6" ref-type="fig">Fig. 6</xref>B; <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S29</ext-link>; FDR &lt; 0.05). The MCMC and Hybrid implementations both identified over 1400 stabilized transcripts, and the MLE implementation identified 449 stabilized transcripts. While the number of transcripts identified as stabilized by the previous analysis strategy (1692) was comparable with the bakR MCMC implementation, we noticed that there were significant differences in the identity of these transcripts (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S30A</ext-link>). The differences were not driven by differences in L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) estimates (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S30B</ext-link>), which were quite similar across analyses. Rather, there were two major causes of the discrepancy. First, the previous analysis did not quantify the uncertainty in the L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) estimate and in many cases inferred stabilization of low coverage transcripts with insufficient data (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF6" ref-type="fig">Fig. 6</xref>C; <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S30C, S31</ext-link>). Second, the previous analysis only considered differentially expressed transcripts, causing it to miss many instances of highly stabilized transcripts that were not identified as significantly up-regulated (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S30D–F, S31</ext-link>). Relying on differential expression analysis can be limiting especially in a case like this where widespread stabilization is expected and the experiment was performed without spike-ins for read count normalization (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC12" ref-type="bibr">Chen et al. 2016</xref>). Alternatively, even with additional normalization, transcripts with significant stabilization in the absence of up-regulation could be due to the increasingly recognized phenomenon of compensatory regulation of transcription to buffer changes in transcript stability (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC71" ref-type="bibr">Sun et al. 2012</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC32" ref-type="bibr">Haimovich et al. 2013</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC1" ref-type="bibr">Abernathy et al. 2015</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC31" ref-type="bibr">Gilbertson et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC7" ref-type="bibr">Berry et al. 2022</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC23" ref-type="bibr">Faucillion et al. 2022</xref>). Either way, bakR provides the first list of <italic>DCP2</italic> KO stabilized transcripts that accounts for L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) estimate uncertainty.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="RNA079451VOCF6">
        <label>FIGURE 6.</label>
        <caption>
          <p>bakR provides an improved statistical foundation to identify biological signals in an existing NR-seq data set. (<italic>A</italic>) Experimental setup used by Luo et al. Transcript stabilities in WT HEK293T were compared with those in <italic>DCP2</italic> knockout (KO) cells. (<italic>B</italic>) Volcano plot obtained from analysis of data with the bakR MCMC implementation. (<italic>C</italic>) Comparison of MA plots obtained with the previous analysis strategy of Luo et al. and the bakR MCMC implementation. (<italic>D</italic>) Correlation between P-body enrichment and DCP2-dependent degradation. (<italic>E</italic>) GSEA analysis using the MCMC stabilized transcripts as the gene set of interest and P-body enrichment scores as the scoring function.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="958f06" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>We next examined the biological implications of the improved analysis. <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC45" ref-type="bibr">Luo et al. (2018)</xref> previously found that transcripts categorized as stabilized in the <italic>DCP2</italic> KO are often associated with P-bodies, which are phase separated granules where the DCP2 protein localizes. We sought to reexamine P-body enrichment while showcasing a promising application of bakR by performing gene-set enrichment analysis (GSEA) using the <italic>DCP2</italic> KO-stabilized transcripts derived from bakR (FDR &lt; 0.05) and P-body enrichment scores from a prior study (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC35" ref-type="bibr">Hubstenberger et al. 2017</xref>). As expected, we found that stabilized transcripts were significantly enriched among P-body transcripts (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF6" ref-type="fig">Fig. 6</xref>D,E; <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S29</ext-link>). Furthermore, bakR amplified this biological signal relative to the previous analysis strategy (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S32</ext-link>). These results confirm that bakR provides an improved statistical foundation to identify biological signals in NR-seq data sets.</p>
      <p>To test the generality of bakR using other NR-seq methods, we reanalyzed data from SLAM-seq with total RNA from <italic>Mettl3</italic> KO mouse embryonic stem cells (mESC) and WT mESC (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC34" ref-type="bibr">Herzog et al. 2017</xref>). Mettl3 is a writer of the m<sup>6</sup>A RNA modification, a mark that has been found to promote degradation of modified transcripts (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC24" ref-type="bibr">Fu et al. 2014</xref>). Using bakR, we identified widespread stabilization in the <italic>Mettl3</italic> KO (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S33</ext-link>) consistent with previous studies. In addition, we performed GSEA analysis but this time using L2FC(<italic>k</italic><sub>deg</sub>) <italic>z</italic>-scores from the bakR MCMC implementation as the scoring function and a list of previously identified Mettl3 targets as the gene set of interest (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC3" ref-type="bibr">Batista et al. 2014</xref>). Mettl3 targets were significantly enriched among the most stabilized transcripts (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Fig. S33</ext-link>). These analyses require the uncertainty quantification provided by bakR and confirm that bakR effectively identifies biological signal while also being applicable to different NR-seq protocols.</p>
    </sec>
  </sec>
  <sec sec-type="discussion" id="s3">
    <title>DISCUSSION</title>
    <p>bakR is the first tool developed to perform differential kinetic analysis using statistical modeling of nucleotide recoding RNA-seq (NR-seq) data. While existing software can analyze individual NR-seq samples (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC74" ref-type="bibr">Uvarovskii and Dieterich 2017</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC36" ref-type="bibr">Jurges et al. 2018</xref>), bakR performs the necessary statistical inference to compare NR-seq data sets. In addition, bakR implements a new Bayesian hierarchical model that improves uncertainty quantification and increases statistical power in these typically low replicate number, high-throughput data sets.</p>
    <p>We included three distinct computational implementations of our Bayesian hierarchical mixture model in bakR (MLE, Hybrid, and MCMC). While the MCMC and Hybrid implementations significantly outperform all other tested implementations, their longer runtimes likely necessitate the use of specialized computation infrastructure (e.g., High Performance Computing) when analyzing typical NR-seq data sets. Therefore, we also provide the MLE implementation as an efficient and often conservative alternative to facilitate rapid exploratory investigations of differential RNA metabolic kinetics.</p>
    <p>We note the comparable performance of the Hybrid and MCMC implementations in most of our simulations (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCF5" ref-type="fig">Fig. 5</xref>; <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S6, S11, S17, S20, S27, S28</ext-link>). These implementations often had a similar FDR, power, and MCC at all significance cutoffs assessed. Despite this as well as the Hybrid implementation's superior efficiency (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Table S1</ext-link>), we included the MCMC implementation in bakR because it offers advantages over the other implementations. The MCMC implementation provides mutation rate estimates that are typically more robust than those provided by the MLE implementation, especially in difficult experimental settings (e.g., short sequencing reads, low mutation rates, etc.) (see <ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Figs. S6, S11, S12, S28</ext-link> for example). The MCMC implementation also includes sampling diagnostics provided by Stan (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC30" ref-type="bibr">Gelman et al. 2015</xref>). Failed convergence of the MCMC implementation's Stan model may indicate subtle anomalies in NR-seq data sets that the other implementations and bakR quality control functions cannot identify. The fully Bayesian model fit provided by the MCMC implementation also opens the door for additional explorations of NR-seq data sets (e.g., mutational data posterior predictive checks) (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC29" ref-type="bibr">Gelman 2014</xref>). Thus, all three computational implementations provided by bakR offer complementary advantages.</p>
    <p>Analysis of simulated data confirmed that bakR can accurately estimate kinetic parameters and differences in kinetic parameters between two samples. Simulations also demonstrated that bakR significantly outperforms differential kinetic analysis with extensions of existing models (the CPNB and NHPMM implementations). We analyzed several existing NR-seq data sets (TimeLapse-seq data in <italic>DCP2</italic> KO and WT 293T cells [<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC46" ref-type="bibr">Luo et al. 2020</xref>] and SLAM-seq data in <italic>Mettl3</italic> KO and WT mESCs [<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC34" ref-type="bibr">Herzog et al. 2017</xref>]) and found that bakR can effectively identify differences that capture biologically relevant changes.</p>
    <p>bakR paired with metabolic labeling, nucleotide recoding chemistry, and RNA-seq significantly facilitates statistically rigorous differential RNA kinetic analysis. bakR uses Bayesian hierarchical modeling to effectively share information across transcripts, increasing its statistical power while maintaining the desired level of specificity. Applying bakR's analysis strategy to the growing list of extensions of NR-seq could provide similar benefits (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC21" ref-type="bibr">Erhard et al. 2019</xref>, <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC22" ref-type="bibr">2022</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC4" ref-type="bibr">Battich et al. 2020</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC11" ref-type="bibr">Cao et al. 2020</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC57" ref-type="bibr">Qiu et al. 2020</xref>, <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC58" ref-type="bibr">2022</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC81" ref-type="bibr">Zimmer et al. 2021</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC67" ref-type="bibr">Smalec et al. 2022</xref>). We anticipate that broad implementation of bakR to analyze NR-seq data sets will provide new insights into the regulated kinetics of gene expression.</p>
    <sec id="s3a">
      <title>Limitations</title>
      <p>bakR implements a Bayesian hierarchical model and downstream statistical inference to facilitate comparisons of RNA kinetics in two or more samples. Currently, bakR is only compatible with comparisons of a set of experimental samples to a single reference sample. Additional comparisons can be performed with bakR, but multiple test adjustment that accounts for the true number of hypothesis tests conducted must be implemented manually.</p>
      <p>In addition, bakR does not perform differential expression analysis, so the output of well-established differential expression software like DESeq2 must be combined with the output of bakR to perform differential RNA synthesis kinetic analysis. We chose to avoid redundant development of differential expression analyses in bakR since several well-validated tools exist for this purpose.</p>
      <p>bakR provides a statistically rigorous analysis of NR-seq data sets. Despite this, factors that arise from challenges in upstream experimental design or execution such as indirect effects of genetic knockouts, batch effects, etc. can cause bakR's conclusions to reflect technical artifacts rather than real biological effects.</p>
      <p>bakR relies on metabolic labeling and nucleotide recoding chemistry, a powerful experimental approach for studying gene expression kinetics (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC19" ref-type="bibr">Duffy et al. 2019</xref>), yet not all biological systems are compatible with metabolic labeling. In those cases, other methods can be used to extract kinetic information from RNA-seq data without metabolic labeling by modeling intronic and exonic read counts (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC25" ref-type="bibr">Furlan et al. 2020</xref>, <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC26" ref-type="bibr">2021</xref>). Unfortunately, these models are underdetermined unless provided with multiple time points of RNA-seq data. Therefore, when possible, NR-seq combined with bakR provides more statistical power to assess differential RNA kinetics with fewer samples.</p>
    </sec>
  </sec>
  <sec sec-type="materials|methods" id="s4">
    <title>MATERIALS AND METHODS</title>
    <sec id="s4a">
      <title>Estimation of the fraction new (<italic>θ</italic>)</title>
      <p>Both of the mixture models considered (new hierarchical model and NHPMM model) were similar to that described by <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC66" ref-type="bibr">Schofield et al. (2018)</xref> and implemented in GRAND-SLAM (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC36" ref-type="bibr">Jurges et al. 2018</xref>). Briefly, we model the number of mutations in sequencing reads from a given transcript (subscript <italic>t</italic>) in a given sample (subscript <italic>s</italic>) as coming from a mixture of two Poisson distributions. One component of the mixture represents the background mutation rate due to sequencing errors in old RNA while the other component models the higher s<sup>4</sup>U recoding augmented mutation rate in new RNA. The likelihood function for this model is
