iant="normal">C</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">t</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">s</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>!</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac></mml:mrow><mml:mo>,</mml:mo></mml:mstyle></mml:mstyle></mml:math></disp-formula>
where TC<sub>t</sub><sub>,s</sub> is the number of mutations in a single sequencing read (T-to-C mutations if using s<sup>4</sup>U; we note that bakR is equally applicable to the analysis of G-to-A mutations in NR-seq experiments performed with s<sup>6</sup>G) (<xref rid="RNA079451VOCC38" ref-type="bibr">Kiefer et al. 2018</xref>; <xref rid="RNA079451VOCC28" ref-type="bibr">Gasser et al. 2020</xref>), <italic>λnew</italic> is the mutation rate in reads from new RNA, and <italic>λold</italic> is the mutation rate in reads from old RNA. The original models used a binomial mixture model rather than a Poisson mixture model, but since the average number of mutations in sequencing reads is typically much lower than the average number of Us (Ts in the sequenced cDNA), the binomial distributions can be approximated with Poisson distributions. The motivation for using this approximation is that a Poisson model yields significant compression of input data and far greater efficiency than a binomial model because it does not track the number of Us in each sequencing read (<ext-link xlink:href="http://www.rnajournal.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1261/rna.079451.122/-/DC1" ext-link-type="uri">Supplemental Table S1</ext-link>). To facilitate parameter estimation, <italic>λnew</italic> and <italic>λold</italic> are global parameters shared by all transcripts in a given sample, so we account for differences in transcript U-contents by calculating the fold difference in transcript-specific and global U content as:
