  <sec id="s8">
    <title>MEET THE FIRST AUTHOR</title>
    <fig position="float" id="d64e8173">
      <caption>
        <p>Isaac Vock</p>
      </caption>
      <graphic xlink:href="958f07" position="float"/>
    </fig>
    <p>
      <bold><italic>Meet the First Author(s)</italic> is an editorial feature within RNA, in which the first author(s) of research-based papers in each issue have the opportunity to introduce themselves and their work to readers of RNA and the RNA research community. Isaac Vock is the first author of this paper, “bakR: uncovering differential RNA synthesis and degradation kinetics transcriptome-wide with Bayesian hierarchical modeling.” Isaac completed his undergraduate degree in Physics at Center College in Danville, Kentucky, and is now a Molecular Biophysics and Biochemistry PhD student in the laboratory of Matthew Simon at Yale University.</bold>
    </p>
    <p>
      <bold>What are the major results described in your paper and how do they impact this branch of the field?</bold>
    </p>
    <p>We introduced bakR, an R package for identifying differences in RNA synthesis and degradation kinetics between two or more biological conditions. bakR is designed to analyze nucleotide recoding RNA-seq experiments (NR-seq; e.g., TimeLapse-seq, SLAM-seq, TUC-seq, etc.), a powerful class of metabolic labeling approaches commonly used to assess the kinetics of gene expression. Like popular tools for differential expression analysis, bakR increases its statistical power by sharing information across transcripts using hierarchical modeling.</p>
    <p>
      <bold>What led you to study RNA or this aspect of RNA science?</bold>
    </p>
    <p>Matt Simon (my PI) presented a short talk to my PhD cohort in our first year where he pitched the idea of developing improved statistical analyses of the RNA-seq extensions recently developed in his laboratory. I was a Physics major and a Math minor with interests in statistical modeling, so this proposal piqued my interest. While I had no previous experience in the field of RNA biology, the laboratory has been an incredible environment in which to get up to speed on an exciting field!</p>
    <p>
      <bold>If you were able to give one piece of advice to your younger self, what would that be?</bold>
    </p>
    <p>Don't be intimidated by coding! My first encounters with programming were intensely negative and I felt that I would never wrap my head around the logic of computer science. Now I am a full-time bioinformatician loving what I do every day. Being able to code is a powerful tool to have in one's arsenal, and I found the key to getting comfortable with programming was the abundance of freely available introductory material that helped me better understand the basics.</p>
    <p>
      <bold>Are there specific individuals or groups who have influenced your philosophy or approach to science?</bold>
    </p>
    <p>My PI, Matt, has been an incredible source of inspiration for me. He has taught me how to think like a bioinformatician and a biochemist, which has helped me better understand what RNA biologists want in the software they use. I have also drawn much inspiration from the output of labs like Wolfgang Huber's and Aviv Regev's. The Regev lab's development of DRiLL and the Huber lab's development of DESeq2 heavily inspired bakR as well as the work I look to complete in the second phase of my PhD.</p>
